{
  "texts": [
    "There, a greater hazard is to be reasonably expected, for the higher relief is associated with higher gravitational potential and thus with a greater conversion into kinetic energy as the given landslide triggers, propagates, and finally halts.",
    "An interesting by-product of our ENN can also be seen in Fig. 11.",
    "There, the high hazard levels estimated for the first two landslide inventories are shown to decay with time.",
    "Moreover, we can also observe that the susceptibility and area density do not necessarily correlate, meaning that the probability of landslide occurrence does not directly correlate with its size.",
    "This was also visible in the raw data shared by Kincey et al. (2021)."
  ]
}